<bioghist>
<head>Biography</head>
<p>Reverend Samuel Orcutt was born sometime around 1824 to James Orcutt and Salina Crosby in Albany, New York.  Orcutt is best known for his extensive history of Bridgeport and outlying areas, Bridgeport and Vicinity, a key text that the Bridgeport History Center refers to again and again.</p>
<p>Orcutt became a minister in the Methodist Episcopal Church, and he preached in New York City and Long Island.  A freak train accident ended his life in 1893.</p>
<p>Other works written by Orcutt include histories of Wolcott, Torrington, New Milford, Derby, Connecticut, and the Native Americans of the Housatonic Valley.</p>
</bioghist>
<scopecontent>
<head>Scope and Content of Collection</head>
<p>Most of the material within the papers of Reverend Orcutt collection relate to his work on the histories of Bridgeport and Stratford, Connecticut, although most of the notes are undated.  They include gravestone transcriptions, genealogical notes, and other general historical notes that he used in his later works.  There are also letters, mostly from the 1870s onwards.</p>
</scopecontent>
<arrangement>
<head>Arrangement</head>
<p>The collection is arranged into three series:  the first relates to Orcutts life and primarily contains correspondence.  Series II focuses on his general research for the various histories he wrote.  The third series is dedicated to the genealogy of the Tomlinson family, due to the extent of material.</p>
</arrangement>
